"after 1076","Petegem-aan-de-Leie, Deinze, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Petegem-aan-de-Leie, Deinze, East Flanders, Belgium","Mortagne-du-Nord, France":"Mortagne-du-Nord, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium","Mortain, Manche, Normandie, France":"Mortain, Manche, Normandy, France","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgique":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tournai","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Turney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Turney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","habitational name from any of the places in northern France called Tournai-sur-Dive (Orne), Tournay-sur-Odon (Calvados), or Tourny (Eure), or occasionally from Tournai in Hainaut (Belgium).","perhaps occasionally an occupational name from Middle English <i>tournei</i>, <i>turnai</i> ‘lawyer’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>tourné</i>), or a nickname from Middle English <i>tournei(en)</i> ‘(to) joust, take part in a tournament’ (Old French <i>torneier</i>). Compare   Turner  ."]}]},{"name":"Everard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was reinforced at the time of the Norman Conquest by a Continental Germanic form introduced to Britain by the Normans. The modern given name may be a transferred use of the surname, but it was in regular use in the Digby family of Rutland from the 15th to the 17th centuries, probably as a survival of the Norman name. It alternated in this family with   Kenelm ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mortagne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Francoise, Herve, Marcel, Philippe, Pierre.","French: topographic name for someone who lived on or near a hill, from Old French <i>montaine</i> ‘hill, (small) mountain’; or a habitational name from any of several places called (La) Montagne, named with the same word.","Shortened form of French   Lamontagne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mountain","meanings":["English (Yorkshire; of Norman origin): topographic name from Middle English <i>mountaine</i> ‘mountain’ (Old French <i>montagne</i>). See   Montagne  .","Irish: either of Norman origin, as 1 above, or a variant of   Manton  .","English: variant of <b>Monkton</b> a habitational name from Monkton (Kent, Somerset), Moor Monkton and Nun Monkton (Yorkshire), Bishop Monkton (Yorkshire), or any of numerous other places called Monkton, named with Old English <i>munuc</i> ‘monk’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Lamontagne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Marcel, Emile, Pierre, Aime, Andre, Fernand, Normand, Gaston, Ovide, Achille.","French:","habitational name for someone from any of several places called La Montagne, or a variant of the topographic name   Montagne   1, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Castellan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (northeastern): variant of   Castellano  .","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Kaštelan</b> or of its variant <b>Kastelan</b>: occupational name from <i>kaštelan</i> ‘castellan, fortress commander’, also ‘warden of a prison’. Compare   Castelan   2.","French (southern): variant of <b>Castella</b>, a southern variant of <b>Châtelain</b> ‘lord (of the manor)’; see   Chatelain  . In part, it is probably of Italian origin (see   Castellano  , compare 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Castellano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Miguel, Enrique, Armando, Carlos, Roberto, Guadalupe, Jesus, Luis, Manuel, Ruben.  Italian Carmine, Rocco, Angelo, Salvatore, Vito, Antonio, Carmela, Cosmo, Battista, Carlo, Dario, Enrico.","Spanish: habitational or ethnic name for someone from Castile.","Italian: habitational name for someone from any of the places called Castello, or a topographic name from <i>castellano</i> (from Latin <i>castellanus</i>), denoting someone who lived or worked in a castle. Compare   Castello  ."]},{"name":"Castelan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Miguel, Francisco, Alejandro, Guadalupe, Concepcion, Felipe, Gerardo, Jorge, Jose Luis, Manuel, Serafin.","Galician (<b>Castelán</b>): generally from Galician <i>castelán</i>, the ethnic name for a Castilian (Castilian <i>castellano</i>). However, in some cases it may be a habitational name from any of the places in Lugo and A Coruña provinces, Spain, called Castelán, or it could be an occupational name denoting a bailiff or steward.","In some cases also an Americanized form of Croatian <b>Kaštelan</b> (see   Castellan   2)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Everard de Mortagne I Castellan Tournai was born in 1060, in Petegem-aan-de-Leie, Deinze, East Flanders, Belgium as the son of Alard I Van Petegem En Eine. He married Hèlvide about 1112, in Avesnes, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 27 October 1110, in Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1060–27 October 1110":"1060–27. oktoober 1110","1060–1110":"1060–1110","1069–1099":"1069–1099","1085–1137":"1085–1137","1095–1138":"1095–1138","–1076":"–1076","1138":"1138","about 1095":"umbes 1095","1137":"1137","1069":"1069","1099":"1099","1110":"1110","27 October 1110":"27. oktoober 1110","1076":"1076","1085":"1085","1095":"1095","1060":"1060","AFT 1076":"pärast 1076","Petegem-aan-de-Leie, Deinze, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Petegem-aan-de-Leie, Dein